\begin_layout Standard
A function is made from three ingredients—three sets, really.
 Two of the sets may contain any types of objects—real numbers in each,
 fruits in one and colors in the other, car companies in one and countries
 in the other, subsets of real numbers in one and polynomials in the other,
 matrices in one and integers in the other—no restrictions.
 The definition of function does not specify.
 These two sets are called the domain
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
domain
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and codomain.
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
codomain
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any set can be the domain of a function, and any set can be the codomain
 of a function.
 The only requirements of a function are placed on the third set.
 This set must contain exactly one ordered pair for each element of the
 domain.
 The order of the elements is important too.
 The first component of each ordered pair must be an element of the domain
 and the second component must be an element of the codomain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A relation, like a function is made from three sets, a domain, a codomain,
 and a set of ordered pairs where the first component of the orderd pair
 is an element of the domain and the second component is an element of the
 codomain.
 Unlike a function, there are no further requirements.
 Thus, a relation can be thought of as a 
\series bold
rela
\series default
xed func
\series bold
tion
\series default
.
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
relation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
function
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It has to adhere to fewer rules.
 Remember, the set of ordered pairs defining a function must contain exactly
 one ordered pair for each element of the domain, but a relation does not
 have this restriction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be precise, even though a relation is composed of three sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is any subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(a,b):a\text{ is in }A\text{ and }b\text{ is in }B\}$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
relation
\series default
 itself.
 The sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are just ingredients in the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify the notation, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(a,b):a\text{ is in }A\text{ and }b\text{ is in }B\}$
\end_inset

 is denoted  
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B$
\end_inset

, read 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 cross 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cartesian product
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 To rephrase then, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are sets, a relation is any subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B$
\end_inset

, and a 
\series bold
function
\series default
 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B$
\end_inset

 containing exactly one ordered pair for each element of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A relation 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 might be given using terse set notation 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\{(a,b)\in A\times B:\text{rule of correspondence}\}$
\end_inset

 such as in
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}\times\mathbb{R}:a^{2}+b^{2}=1\}.
\]

\end_inset

The same relation might be simplified to just 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+b^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 if it is understood without writing explicitly that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are real numbers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a relation is a function
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
notation!function
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we may emphasize this point using the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to B$
\end_inset

, read 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Implied in this notation is that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function and there exists a rule of correspondence specifying exactly
 which ordered pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in A\times B$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 To define a specific function, the familiar function notation is often
 used, as in 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a)=\text{"insert formula here"}$
\end_inset

, meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(a,b)\in A\times B:b=\text{"insert formula here"}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The domain and codomain of a function are often taken for granted, fading
 into the background in favor of focusing on the rule of correspondence,
 such as in 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=3x+11$
\end_inset

.
 It is just assumed or implied that the codomain is the set of all real
 numbers and the domain is some subset of the real numbers—with good reason.
 It would be rather repetitive to write 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 every time a function on the real numbers came up.
 More importantly, though, the domains of many functions with succinct formulas
 do not contain all real numbers.
 The domain only includes numbers that correspond to some element of the
 codomain.
 It would be a difficult distraction to have to write 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and get the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 correct every time a function was mentioned.
 To be complete, though, the definition of a function should include this
 information, and it is a convenience not to require it.
 To compensate for this lack of completeness in practice, a classic problem
 in algebra is to find the 
\shape italic
implied
\shape default
 domain of functions such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\frac{3x+7}{2x-5}$
\end_inset

—the subset of real number inputs that correspond to real number outputs
 according to the formula.
 Can you find the implied domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\frac{3x+7}{2x-5}$
\end_inset

? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:implied-domain"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discussion of inverse functions
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
inverse function
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which will be very important for us, is made abstruse by not introducing
 the notion of a relation.
 The inverse of a relation is a relatively simple matter.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a relation with domain 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and codomain 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, the relation with domain 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and codomain 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}=\{(b,a):(a,b)\text{ is in }C\}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
inverse relation
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
inverse relation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Every relation has an inverse relation, no exceptions.
 Simply reversing the order of the ordered pairs in any relation gives its
 inverse.
 Consequently every function (which is just a special type of relation)
 has an inverse 
\shape italic
relation
\shape default
, and the inverse is conceptually straightforward.
 That is not to say that the inverse relation is always a function, however.
 There are plenty of functions that do not have inverse functions, and tackling
 this problem before tackling the simpler one of inverse relations is the
 root of much confusion and difficulty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Maps and Transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Map
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
map
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\series bold
mapping
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
mapping
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and 
\series bold
transformation
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
transformation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are all synonyms for function.
 All four words share the same definition.
 When the codomain is not the set of real numbers, the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is often supplanted by one of the others.
 Getting used to this fact is a matter of experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $3n+1$
\end_inset

 conjecture is that iteration (computing the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $n,R(n),R(R(n)),R(R(R(n))),\ldots$
\end_inset

) of the 
\shape italic
mapping
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R:\mathbb{Z}^{+}\to\mathbb{Z}^{+}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R(n)=\begin{cases}
\frac{n}{2} & \text{if }n\text{ is even}\\
3n+1 & \text{if }n\text{ is odd}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

always ends with the cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $4,2,1,4,2,1,\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 Try it starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=13$
\end_inset

, for example.
 How many iterations does it take to get the first 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:3n-plus-one-problem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Don't get too distracted, though.
 The point here is that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a mapping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\shape italic
transformation
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}:C(D)\to C^{1}(D)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}(f)=\int_{0}^{x}f(t)\,dt$
\end_inset

 is a standard of calculus, though it is less common to discuss the antiderivati
ve as a transformation during a calculus class.
 The derivative provides another example of a 
\shape italic
transformation
\shape default
 from some set of functions to another set of functions.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $D:\mathbb{P}_{n}(\mathbb{R})\to\mathbb{P}_{n-1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $D(p)=p'(x)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\shape italic
map
\shape default
 from the set of polynomials of degree at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to the set of polynomials of degree at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=3x^{2}-2x+1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D(p)=p'(x)=6x-2$
\end_inset

.
 Mechanically there is no advantage to writing the derivative as a 
\shape italic
transformation
\shape default
, but conceptually it gives a certain perspective on the process of differentiat
ion.
 The process itself can be thought of as a function!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\shape italic
map
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $l:\mathbb{R}^{\mathbb{N}}\to\mathbb{R}^{\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $l(s_{0},s_{1},s_{2},\ldots)=s_{1},s_{2},s_{3},\ldots$
\end_inset

 is sometimes called the (left) shift operator.
 Its cousin, the left bit shift operator (called left-shift) plays a huge
 role in computing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The determinant is a function or 
\shape italic
map
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det:\mathcal{M}_{n\times n}(\mathbb{F})\to\mathbb{F}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 since each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix has exactly one determinant.
 The 
\shape italic
transformation
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z:GL_{n}(\mathbb{F})\to GL_{n}(\mathbb{F})$
\end_inset

 
\shape italic
mapping
\shape default
 an invertible matrix to its inverse provides motivation to think of finding
 the inverse of a matrix as a function as well.
 The most common 
\shape italic
transformation
\shape default
 considered in linear algebra, however, is the 
\shape italic
transformation
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x})=M\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 for some matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 defined this way have two properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y})=T(\mathbf{x})+T(\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $T(c\mathbf{x})=cT(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can you justify this claim? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:two-properties"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 These two properties mean that performing addition and scalar multiplication
 in the domain and then transforming (the lefthand sides of the equations)
 gives the same result as transforming first and then performing the addition
 and scalar multiplication in the codomain (the righthand sides of the equations
).
 For this reason we say this type of transformation preserves the operations
 of addition and scalar multiplication.
 Its properties form the essence for the abstraction of this idea to arbitrary
 vector spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Linear Transformations
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
linear transformation
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

|(
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given vector spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, a 
\series bold
linear transformation
\series default
 is any transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $L:V\to W$
\end_inset

 such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $L(x+y)=L(x)+L(y)$
\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $L(cx)=cL(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This definition is modeled after 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x})=M\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, making 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 the canonical example of a linear transformation.
 Some of the other transformations mentioned in this section are linear
 transformations and some are not.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is not since 
\begin_inset Formula $R(2+3)=16$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $R(2)+R(3)=1+10=11$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $11\neq16$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to find positive integers that violate property 1.
 The derivative is a linear transformation since two basic results of calculus
 are that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f+g)'=f'+g'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(cf)'=cf'$
\end_inset

.
 These rules of differentiation say precisely that properties 1 and 2 hold
 when differentiation is viewed as a mapping.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f+g)=D(f)+D(g)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(cf)=cD(f)$
\end_inset

.
 What about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A},l,\det,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

? Are they linear? Answers on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:linear-or-not"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

