\begin_layout Standard
It is not an accident that the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is used for the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 The notion of an inverse function extends the idea of multiplicative (and
 additive) inverses.
 By definition, if 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 has an inverse function 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}(T(a))=a$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Can you justify this claim? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
