Another two results of calculus are that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int(f+g)=\int f+\int g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int(cf)=c\int f$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}(f+g)=\mathcal{A}(f)+\mathcal{A}(g)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}(cf)=c\mathcal{A}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is a linear transformation.
 On one hand,
\begin_inset Formula $l(s+t)=l\left((s_{0},s_{1},s_{2},\ldots)+(t_{0},t_{1},t_{2},\ldots)\right)=l\left(s_{0}+t_{0},s_{1}+t_{1},s_{2}+t_{2},\ldots\right)=s_{1}+t_{1},s_{2}+t_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $l(s)+l(t)=l(s_{0},s_{1},s_{2},\ldots)+l(t_{0},t_{1},t_{2},\ldots)=(s_{1},s_{2},\ldots)+(t_{1},t_{2},\ldots)=s_{1}+t_{1},s_{2}+t_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $l(s+t)=l(s)+l(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Property 1 holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 To check that property 2 holds, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $l(cs)=l(cs_{0},cs_{1},cs_{2},\ldots)=cs_{1},cs_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $cl(s)=cl(s_{0},s_{1},s_{2},\ldots)=c(s_{1},s_{2},\ldots)=cs_{1},cs_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

 too.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det$
\end_inset

 is not a linear transformation.
 For example, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 3\\
3 & 5
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=-A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=\det B=1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A)+\det(B)=2$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A+B)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Matrix inversion is also not a linear transformation.
 Using the same matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 & -3\\
-3 & 2
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-5 & 3\\
3 & -2
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 so the sum of the inverses is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 but the inverse of the sum does not exist.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $V(A)+V(B)=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $V(A+B)$
\end_inset

 does not exist, so they are not equal.
\end_layout

